\begin_layout Standard
The form of possible inverse square law violations is not known from first
 principles.
 However, under the assumption that a new interaction can be modelled by
 a Yukawa potential (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:YukawaPotential"

\end_inset

), the new force between flat plates is calculable.
 Neglecting edge effects, if one plate is infinite in spatial extent, the
 other has area 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and the plates have densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

, thicknesses 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

, and face-to-face separation 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, the Yukawa force 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{Y}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{Y}=2\pi G\rho_{1}\rho_{2}A\alpha\lambda^{2}\left(1-e^{-t_{1}/\lambda}\right)\left(1-e^{-t_{2}/\lambda}\right)e^{-d/\lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the plate size, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, is large compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, the fractional error from end effects should be roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim4\lambda\sqrt{A}/A=4\lambda/\sqrt{A}$
\end_inset

.
 In our experiment, with a parallel orientation, this correction spans 0.1-10%
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m), and always acts to increase the magnitude of the signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, the Yukawa interaction is indistinguishable from an altered 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{Y}\rightarrow2\pi G\rho_{1}\rho_{2}A\alpha t_{1}t_{2}$
