\begin_layout Subsubsection
Foil-stretcher design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The design of the mechanism for stretching foils is important.
 The foil must be flat and tightly stretched.
 More recently, it has become clear that the foil surface must be easy to
 access and clean.
 In the past, our group has constructed foils by clamping beryllium-copper
 foils between strong aluminum rings while the entire assembly was submerged
 in liquid nitrogen.
 Upon warming to room temperature, the differential expansion of the aluminum
 rings brought the foil to high uniform tension.
 This arrangement offers superior rigidity, but the clamping rings do not
 provide sufficient access to the foil face.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The PlateWash foil stretcher is designed to provide good access to the front
 face of the foil and excellent flatness.
 It is constructed much as one would make a bongo drum; a clamping ring
 holds the foil at its perimeter, and a rounded-edge inner 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pusher
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that pushes on the back of the foil to bring it up to tension.
 Key to the success of this design is the rounded edge of the inner pusher.
 The radius of the edge must be large compared to the foil thickness in
 order to completely determine the state of the foil at the position of
 last contact.
 The radius of the edge should continue well past the point of last contact,
 to ensure a smooth transition, without any burrs or varying radial position
 of last contact.
 Furthermore, after turning, sanding, and polishing on the lathe, the pusher
 should be gently lapped, just for a moment, on a granite inspection plate
 to make the final planarization of the point of last contact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to enable excellent access to the foil face, but preserve uniform
 tension in the foil, it is essential that the front ring of the foil clamping
 ring be very thin.
 In the case of PlateWash, with parallel fiber/foil alignment, the fiber
 is separated by only a millimeter from the foil face.
 The front clamping ring is only 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1.2$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

mm thick.
 This allows the foil to remain nearly flat when being tensioned, requiring
 minimum slack in the foil to permit the foil pusher to come into tension
 while permitting full access to the foil face.
 In this iteration of the experiment, the front ring does not retreat behind
 the foil face, requiring a slight deflection of the fiber screw and inclination
 of the apparatus in order to clear the torsion fiber.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dimensions of the entire instrument are partially-set by the availability
 of thin foils.
 We were unable to find strong metal foils of thickness 
\begin_inset Formula $<12$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m in widths larger than 4 inches.
 This constrains the inner bore of the foil stretcher, hence the size of
 the attractor, and therefore size of the pendulum.
\end_layout

