As Saulson and GonzÃ¡lez neatly described 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saulson1990thermal,Gonz\\'alez199512,1995PhDT........16G"

\end_inset

, all mechanical oscillators have intrinsic thermal noise.
 Through the fluctuation-dissipation theorem, any lossy oscillator at finite
 temperature drives itself with thermal fluctuations.
 The intrinsic noise in a torsion balance is known to be consistent with
 thermal noise from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

internal damping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, that is, that the spring constant has an imaginary part.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I\ddot{\theta}=\kappa\theta\rightarrow I\ddot{\theta}=\kappa(1+i\frac{1}{Q})\theta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is the torsion constant of the fiber, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 the pendulum's moment of inertia about the fiber axis, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the oscillator quality factor, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 the pendulum twist angle.
 This is in contrast to more-familiar external damping, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I\ddot{\theta}=-\kappa\theta-\frac{\sqrt{\kappa I}}{Q}\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A torsion balance suspended in sufficiently high vacuum is `internally damped'.
 Following Saulson's classic explication, internal damping gives rise to
 torque noise power with a 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

