\begin_layout Subsubsection
Contact potential noise
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Contact-potential-noise"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Electrical connections generally form small galvanic batteries 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lamoreaux1997demonstration"

\end_inset

.
 Numerous connections in series between, for example, the pendulum and foil,
 give rise to a small (
\begin_inset Formula $<1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

V) potential between them that is fairly stable (
\begin_inset Formula $<10$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

mV/month drift), and initially unpredictable in value.
 For this experiment, fluctuations in contact potential are indistinguishable
 from noise from a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

patch effect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, except, perhaps, through the distance-dependence of the noise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The influence of any contact-potential noise, either through direct fluctuation
 or through swing-coupling can be minimized by nulling the contact potential.
 The force acting between plates of a parallel-plate capacitor with area
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, plate separation 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, and potential difference 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $|F|=\epsilon_{0}A\frac{V_{0}^{2}}{d^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 For small variations in voltage (
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}\rightarrow V_{0}+\delta v)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|F|=\epsilon_{0}\frac{A}{d^{2}}(V_{0}^{2}+2V_{0}\delta V+(\delta V)^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, nulling 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 can minimize the effect of any voltage fluctuation.
 Similarly, for swing, where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\rightarrow d_{0}+\delta d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|F|=\epsilon_{0}\frac{AV_{0}^{2}}{(d_{0}+\delta d)^{2}}$
\end_inset

, so the swing coupling is quadratically suppressed by minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We carefully designed battery-powered isolated and remotely-operable power
 supplies to permit the nulling of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

, and demonstrated control of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 at better than the 100 mV level.
 Swing parallel to the foil, which we expect to have approximately equal
 amplitude, should cause much smaller variations in electrostatic torques
 acting on the pendulum, as only the effective lever-arm of the pendulum
 may be altered.
 If the contact potential varies across the foil plane, parallel-swing torques
 will come primarily from that variation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, the presence of an uncompensated contact potential acts as
 an anti-spring for the pendulum, pulling the torsion pendulum asymptotically
 away from its zero position.
 As the pendulum twists away from a parallel orientation with respect to
 the foil, the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}^{2}/d^{2}$
\end_inset

 nature of the capacitive force pulls even harder.
 Once the capacitive torque is greater than the torsion fiber restoring
 torque, the pendulum runs away toward the foil.
 As our sensitivity to new physics increases exponentially with smaller
 pendulum/foil separation, we are driven to operate the pendulum at the
 smallest distance at which we can preserve stable operation of the pendulum.
 Compensation of the contact potential allows us to operate with lower noise
 at closer distances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, in tracking down the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

capacitor systematic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Capacitor-Systematic"

\end_inset

