\begin_layout Chapter
Strategic choices and operation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter describes important strategies and choices we made in the operation
 of the instrument: selecting the signal frequency, selecting the pendulum-angle
 signal as our science signal, random attractor locations, and the overall
 distribution of attractor locations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Frequency-space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each PlateWash measurement operates in a frequency regime spanning 100
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

Hz to 1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Hz.
 This section describes the way in which important experimental frequencies
 were selected.
 The most-important frequency, the frequency with which the attractor changes
 position, is pushed by several concerns to the highest-feasible frequency.
 The limit of feasibility is set by both the limited speed with which our
 attractor drive can operate and by the speed with which the pendulum feedback
 control can react without adding extra noise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spectral Character of Noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our torsion balance is an excellent harmonic oscillator.
 For quality torsion fibers operated at amplitudes much smaller than a radian,
 the anharmonic terms are negligible
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In a precise measurement in beryllium-copper at 77K on a 
\begin_inset Formula $20$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m diameter fiber with 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\sim10^{-7}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

N-m/rad, with a parametrization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa(\theta)=\kappa_{1}+\kappa_{2}\theta+\kappa_{3}\theta^{2}$
\end_inset

, Bantel and Newman found 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{2}/\kappa<4\times10^{-7}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

rad
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{3}/\kappa<5\times10^{-8}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

rad
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bantel2000high"

\end_inset

.
 For this experiment, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\sim10^{-8}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

N-m/rad, maximum angles of < 1 mrad, and a torque goal of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-16}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

N-m, a 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{2}/\kappa$
\end_inset

 ratio as large as 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

rad
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 would yield a sufficiently linear response.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{2}\cdot10^{-6}=10^{-16}\rightarrow\kappa_{2}=10^{-10}\rightarrow\kappa_{2}/\kappa=10^{-2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The torque-to-angle transfer function of an internally-damped torsion oscillato
r with resonant angular frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, torsion spring constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

, moment of inertia 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and quality factor 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SchlammingerWallet"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(\omega)=\left|\frac{\theta(\omega)}{\tau(\omega)}\right|=\frac{1/\kappa}{\sqrt{(1-\omega^{2}/\omega_{0}^{2})^{2}+1/Q^{2}}};\Rightarrow\mbox{If }\omega\gg\omega_{0},\,\left|\frac{\theta(\omega)}{\tau(\omega)}\right|\rightarrow\frac{1}{I\omega^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots/pwTransferFunction.eps
	width 70page%
	scaleBeforeRotation

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Approximate torque-to-angle transfer function
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Approximate-torque-to-angle-tran"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\gg\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, the pendulum response is independent of the torsion spring.
 This is the torque equivalent of 
\begin_inset Formula $F=ma=m\ddot{x}\rightarrow\tilde{\tau}=I(-\omega^{2})\tilde{\theta}$
\end_inset

 ; at these frequencies, the pendulum acts like a free mass.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\ll\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, the pendulum response is frequency independent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Thermal Noise 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Fiber-thermal-noise"

\end_inset

, the torque noise power of a thermally-limited torsion balance is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau^{2}(f)=4k_{B}T\frac{\kappa}{2\pi fQ}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This drives any measurement toward higher frequencies for decreased noise.
 In power spectral amplitude, the improvement only comes as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{f}$
\end_inset

, implying that the benefit of increased frequency is limited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convolving this noise with the torque-to-angle transfer function (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Approximate-torque-to-angle-tran"

\end_inset

), we recover the angle noise spectrum of a thermally-limited torsion oscillator.
 
\end_layout

