\begin_layout Subsection
Statistics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Statistics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The higher the attractor frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, the more individual measurements we can make.
 In principle, given frequency-independent noise, the choice of signal frequency
 is arbitrary.
 If the noise power-spectral-density 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\omega)=S_{0}$
\end_inset

, then the resulting uncertainty of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 measurements each of duration 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{m}=1/f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{all}=\sqrt{\frac{S_{0}}{Nt_{m}}}$
\end_inset

.
 If the measurements are performed in a fixed time 
\begin_inset Formula $T=Nt$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{all}=\sqrt{\frac{S_{0}}{T}}$
\end_inset

, independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Practically, however, noise is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

non-Gaussian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is both time and frequency-dependent.
 Sudden/prominent events including earthquakes, human activity, attractor/foil
 interactions, and computer crashes happen.
 They are often short in duration, but overwhelming in amplitude.
 Measurements taken at these times are unusable.
 In this experiment, such transients happened at most a few times in a day.
 It will be shown in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Filtering"

\end_inset

 that for any large transient, measurements for at least 
\begin_inset Formula $30t_{m}=7680\mbox{\,\ s}=2.1\mbox{\,\ hr}$
\end_inset

 must be discarded.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{m}$
\end_inset

 were smaller, the experiment's fractional dead-time would be smaller.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second benefit to small 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the increased number of independent measurements.
 This experiment relies upon Monte-Carlo-like measurements (random attractor
 locations) to constrain both systematic uncertainties and possible violations
 of the inverse-square law.
 Frequent individual measurements allow faster exploration of parameter
 space (exploring a 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 grid of measurements requires a day with the current choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{m}$
\end_inset

).
 Measurements that are twice as frequent allow twice as many questions to
 be answered, albeit with precision degraded by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
 When noise is frequency-independent, there is no penalty for this approach.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Faster switching is better, much more than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\mbox{better}}$
\end_inset

