\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linearity and limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is traditional in this field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cook2013,Kapner2005"

\end_inset

 to assume that the effective uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}_{G}$
\end_inset

 for a model quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $G(a_{1},\ldots,a_{n})$
\end_inset

, with measured uncertainties 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{a_{1}},\ldots,\sigma_{a_{n}}$
\end_inset

 can be estimated (for the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th measurement) by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\sigma}_{G_{j}}^{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\sigma_{a_{i_{j}}}\left.\frac{\partial G}{\partial a_{i}}\right|_{\{a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\}=\{a_{1_{j}},\ldots a_{n_{j}}\}}\right)^{2}\label{eq:Linearized Variance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 is then de-weighted by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\sum_{j=1}^{N}\frac{(\Delta\tau_{j}-\bar{G}_{j})^{2}}{\sigma_{\Delta\tau_{j}}^{2}+\tilde{\sigma}_{G_{j}}^{2}}\label{eq:X2 Statement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This approach is appropriate when the linearization of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is appropriate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of PlateWash, it is clear from inspection of Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PrototypeFitFunction"

\end_inset

 that when the effective Yukawa interaction range 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 becomes comparable to, or smaller than, the precision with which the attractor
 position is determined, the experimental sensitivity should be degraded.
 In the linearization approach, this corresponds to a diverging 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}_{f}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, linearizing 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-x/\lambda}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}\gtrsim\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a recipe for trouble.
 With aid and inspiration from Jason Detwiler, we computed the full non-linear
 variance of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PrototypeDifferenceFunction"

\end_inset

, shown in full detail in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Yukawa-Variance-and"

\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Detwiler Trick
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is worth a look).
 While we succeded, this entire approach has a fatal flaw; the flaw is in
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Linearized Variance"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Flaw
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flaw is easy to see qualitatively.
 In Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X2 Statement"

\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

 diverges, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 is driven to zero.
 Any 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-minimizing fitter will, given the opportunity, exploit this to favor locations
 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is huge.
 Thus, fits with smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 are incorrectly preferred over perfectly reasonable fits with larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Nikolai Tolich was the first of those with whom we conferred to reach a
 quantitative understanding of the problem.
 
\end_layout

