\begin_layout Subparagraph
Advantage - systematic metrology uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bootstrapped handling of uncertainties allows a trivial inclusion of
 a traditionally difficult-to-handle uncertainty, colloquially known as
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

horizontal systematic errorbars
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 As the determination of the absolute separation of the pendulum and foil,
 and hence the pendulum and attractor is necessarily uncertain (see Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Uncertainty-table-distance"

\end_inset

), this must be reflected in degraded confidence intervals at small 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 From the perspective of our global fit, this measurement is unchanging,
 making it a systematic uncertainty (and, indeed, it contains its own systematic
 uncertainties).
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzzing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 process introduced above is readily adapted to this concern.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each iteration of the bootstrapped fit, in addition to individually
 randomly displacing each position measurement by its individual statistical
 uncertainty, we displace 
\bar under
all
\bar default
 positions by a single random amount, distributed by the known metrology
 uncertainty.
 This approach naturally incorporates our absolute position uncertainty
 without degrading our known and meaningful differential position sensitivity.
\end_layout

