\begin_layout Standard
There is no unique method for drawing two-dimensional confidence intervals.
 The method we selected was chosen for its clarity after exploring more
 sophisticated methods (kernel density estimators among them).
 The most important lesson from our investigation of differing methods is
 the notion that, 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
, the Yukawa 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 have nothing to do with one another.
 Any attempt to constrain them jointly makes a prior assumption about their
 relationship.
 The long-standing tradition in this field is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pick a lambda and fit for alpha
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approach, which sidesteps any presupposition of covariance.
 What we do is in that spirit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outcome of the bootstrapped Yukawa fits is a distribution of best-fit
 points in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-\lambda$
\end_inset

 plane.
 Working from small 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 to large 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, we compute the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

s of the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 composed of the first 
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../extracted/NBinConfInterval.tex"

\end_inset

 best-fit point.
 This number is chosen as the square-root of the number of bootstrapped
 points in order to limit over-zealous fluctuations of the confidence interval
 curves.
 We then plot four points, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{min},m_{\alpha}\pm2\sigma_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{max},m_{\alpha}\pm2\sigma_{\alpha})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{min}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{max}$
\end_inset

 are the smallest and largest 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

s of points in the subset.
 We then remove the point corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{min}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, add the next point with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{max}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, and repeat the procedure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two envelopes defined by the four lines that emerge define the 95% confidenc
e intervals for our best fits.
 Regions that are excluded by both envelopes are certainly excluded at 95%
 confidence.
 Regions that are included by both are included at 95% confidence.
 Regions excluded by only one envelope are indeterminate; we've roughly
 quantified the uncertainty on our confidence interval.
 The volume of the indeterminate region can be made arbitrarily small by
 computing greater numbers of best-fit points.
 In regions where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a strong function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, convergence is necessarily slow.
 The final confidence-interval plots can be found in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Yukawa-Potential-Constraints"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

