\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
If a signal is resolved
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It might be new physics, it might be one of the above systematic effects,
 or it might be something we missed.
 While that sentence is tautological, it leads us forward.
 If the signal is new physics, it will survive future tests.
 It is possible to evaluate many of the above systematics readily, in some
 cases with external measurements, in others by repeating the measurement
 with upgrades.
 If the systematic is something inherent to our apparatus, repeated experiments
 by others in the field, or with completely different designs, like our
 group's wedge-pendulum apparatus, will help to improve everyone's understanding
 of Nature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any repetition of our experiment should be performed blind.
 Remaining blind has helped us so much in identifying previously unknown
 systematics and properly characterizing known ones.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
If a signal is not resolved
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Everything in the resolved-signal section above applies.
